result.execSummary:
The defendant Juan C. Delgado was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Endanger Safety/Use/Dangerous Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.20(1)(a).
  • Carry Concealed Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.23(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
2:00 PM Defendant Juan C. Delgado appeared by video.  Attorney Marsolek in court for State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Carly June Sebion appeared by video for Juan C. Delgado. State in compliance with victim rights notification. Defendant understands and agrees to appear remotely. Defendant entered a plea of No Contest to both counts. 

Court reviewed the elements and potential penalties of the charge the defendant plead to.  He understood.   Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant. He understood. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of  Endanger Safety/Use/Dangerous Weapon contrary to 941.20(1)(a), Carry Concealed Weapon contrary to 941.23(2). Defendant did not exercise his right to allocution. 

Joint recommendation: Withhold sentence, 2 yrs probation w/conditions of costs, DNA, Risk and needs assessment, Mental Health evaluation and comply w/agents recommendations, Not possess a firearm during term of probation. 4 days jail credit. Parties agree to expunction. Bond on file applied to costs. 

Atty Sebion  makes request for expunction. No other charges on his record. State in agreement with that request. 

Court adopts the joint recommendation, Withholds sentence, orders 2 yrs probation. Conditions: Defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions. Comply with and follow any directives of the current treating Psychiatrist or treating Dr. must sign a release, provide to probation agent & comply w/ all directives made. Not to possess a firearm during term of probation. 4 days jail credit. Parties agree to expunction. Pay costs on each action. Court cost to be deducted from Bond on file, remaining bond returned to poster.  Ordered to submit DNA sample. Court finds based on given facts, if he successfully discharges from probation w/out any violations or revocations he may expunge his record.

Plea/sentencing hearing on June 29, 2022 at 02:00 pm.
